  "timeframe": "5m",
  "market_context": "Gold's hourly candle closed back inside the previous range, signaling a bearish daily bias. On the 5-minute chart, price had already shifted state of delivery lower, with the previous day low marked as the draw on liquidity aligned with standard deviation projections (-1, -2, -2.5).",
  "key_observation": "Rather than chasing the initial bearish move, the analyst waits for price to retrace into a fair value gap and form a new order block via closure through up-close candles, capturing the continuation leg toward the previous day low.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Establish bearish bias from the 3-hour/hourly closure back inside the range, expecting price to trade lower.",
    "Step 2: Drop to the 5-minute chart and mark the previous day low as the draw on liquidity, aligned with -1, -2, -2.5 standard deviation projections.",
    "Step 3: Confirm the change in state of delivery has already occurred to the downside.",
    "Step 4: Instead of chasing, identify potential points of interest (fair value gaps) since no clean swing highs exist for a sell.",
    "Step 5: Mark multiple fair value gaps above and wait for price to retrace into one, without trying to predict which gap forms the high.",
    "Step 6: Price tags the highest fair value gap; analyst waits for a closure through the series of up-close candles to confirm the new protected high.",
    "Step 7: Enter short on the closure through, stop above the new high, targeting the previous day low.",
    "Step 8: Price validates the new high by closing below the relevant level and expands lower to take out the previous day low / target."
  ],
  "outcome": "Trade reached target — price took out the previous day low, achieving approximately 2.13 risk/reward as shown on the position sizing tool.",
  "lessons": "You do not need to catch the initial reversal; waiting for a continuation entry via a fair value gap retest and closure through up-close candles offers a higher-probability setup with confirmed structure and defined risk.",
